In a briefing, Ben Rhodes, the Press Secretary, provides a readout of the meeting between President Obama and Prime Minister Abe of Japan. They discussed the situation in Syria and agreed on the need for a strong international response to the use of chemical weapons. They also discussed alliance issues, including the TPP and the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula. They expressed their opposition to any coercive efforts to resolve the Senkakus issue and discussed defense issues in the alliance. They also discussed the need to implement the shared plan on the Futenma realignment. Rhodes also mentions that the President will be making phone calls to members of Congress to seek their support for military action in Syria. He also discusses the President's upcoming dinner with world leaders at the G20 summit, where he will make the case for a military response to the use of chemical weapons in Syria. Rhodes also mentions that Prime Minister Abe invited President Obama to visit Japan, to which the President expressed his desire to go. Rhodes also addresses concerns from emerging market economies about the impact of U.S. monetary policy and the need for countries to invest in economic growth. He also discusses the support for military action in Syria from U.S. allies and the importance of U.S. leadership in enforcing international norms. Rhodes concludes by mentioning that he is not aware of any cancellation of a visit to the U.S. by the Brazilian President over the NSA surveillance issue.